  "Idea": "This paper introduces a novel framework called 'Geometric Diagnostics for Semivalue Verification' (GDSV), which shifts the paradigm from proving unconditional #P-hardness of linear optimization over the semivalue polytope $ C_{p^{n+2}} $ to characterizing the *effective complexity* of this task under realistic conditions. While prior work aims to establish worst-case intractability, GDSV investigates whether the optimization landscape over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $—the space of all symmetric, efficient semivalues for n+2 players—exhibits exploitable structure in practice, such as low intrinsic dimensionality, concentration of measure, or piecewise-flat regions, that could enable efficient approximation or certification of explanations for linear threshold functions (LTFs). We hypothesize that although exact optimization is #P-hard, the solution function mapping data distributions to optimal semivalues lies in a low-complexity function class due to symmetries and marginal consistency constraints inherent in cooperative games. To formalize this, we develop a diagnostic toolkit combining convex geometry, empirical process theory, and tame geometry (o-minimal structures) to analyze the covering number, Rademacher complexity, and gradient spectrum of the solution operator over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $. We then introduce a notion of 'verification resilience': a measure of how robustly a given attribution vector (e.g., from Shapley or Banzhaf sampling) resists perturbation within the polytope under a task-specific objective. By analyzing synthetic and real-world LTFs trained on benchmark datasets (e.g., UCI credit scoring), we show that many instances lie in 'benign' regions of the polytope where local search or projected gradient ascent can efficiently certify near-optimality, even when global optimization is intractable. Crucially, we link this to the concept of 'explanation stability'—if small changes in input features induce small shifts in the optimal semivalue, then the veri